******
[1] Germany
Date: Fri 12 Oct 2018
Source: Sabine Zange <sabinezange@bundeswehr.org> [edited]


This is a follow-up report on the suspected case of West Nile virus (WNV) infection in a 31-year-old veterinarian (ProMED-mail archive number 20181006.6074497, published 6 Oct 2018) who had dissected a WNV-positive owl (ProMED-mail archive number 20180914.6029586, published 14 Sep 2018) at a bird clinic in Bavaria, Germany.

We received another serum sample for examination, which the patient had drawn from himself (and since stored frozen at minus 20 deg C) 10 days after the presumed time of infection, which was 3 weeks earlier than the post-acute phase sample reported positive for WNV antibodies in our 1st posting. When the earlier sample was recovered, the clinical symptoms of the 1st episode of fever were decreasing but still present. As already reported, the patient had a history of past vaccinations against tick-borne encephalitis (TBE; during childhood) and yellow fever (YF) virus (in 2012).

We now examined the 2 serum samples in parallel and could show IgM seroconversion to WNV, along with a significant increase in IgG antibody titres against WNV and other flaviviruses between the 2 specimens. Although no IgM antibodies against WNV were detectable in the 1st serum sample by use of an indirect immunofluorescence assay, the sample recovered later showed the presence of IgM antibodies against WNV with a titre of 1:80. No IgM antibodies against dengue (DEN) virus, TBE virus, YF virus and Japanese encephalitis (JE) virus were present in either of the 2 sera. The 1st serum sample showed IgG antibody titres against WNV of 1:10 and against TBE, YF, JE and DEN viruses of 1:40, 1:10,

