[2] Corsica, France
Date: Fri 12 Oct 2018
Source: Corsematin [in French, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
https://www.corsematin.com/article/article/premier-cas-humain-de-virus-west-nile-en-corse


The 1st human case of West Nile virus in Corsica, France has been reported. The person visited the island on holiday and then moved there from Alpes-Maritimes. In addition, 2 horses were reported with the virus in Upper Corsica. The regional health agency (ARS) renews its message of prevention against mosquito bites: "Fight against breeding sites (eliminate stagnant water), [and] use repellents recommended by pharmacists."

Vigilance against mosquito bites is more necessary than ever, as the ARS of Corsica confirms that a person on holiday on the island is currently being treated for West Nile fever, a virus transmitted by the _Culex_ mosquito (the most common, which stings morning, noon and night).

No information has been issued on the patient's current state of health. "We know that this is a person who came on holiday [to] Corsica around [17-18 Sep 2018] and then moved on the island from the Alpes-Maritimes. [As the incubation time of the disease] is between 3 and 15 days, it is very likely that [the person] was bitten by a mosquito in Paca, where there are currently 22 confirmed human cases. The person then developed the symptoms here in Corsica. [I] cannot say that the person was not infected on the island," says Joseph Magnavacca, the director of public health and medico-social at the ARS of Corsica. Therefore, the probability that the virus is autochthonous exists but cannot be verified.

West Nile virus affects the nervous system, but "in most cases, the human infection of West Nile is asymptomatic," i.e., the patient has no symptoms or a mild flulike condition (fever, pain, headache), explains Dr. Anne-Marie McKenzie, doctor of watch and health safety at the ARS of Corsica. "[Thus, the infection often passes unnoticed, but in some rare cases, as for this holidaymaker, the infection is much more serious and affects the nervous system]."

Known by epidemiologists since the 1960s, this virus is transmitted to mosquitoes by migratory birds in sub-Saharan Africa. The insect that stings the infected bird then transmits the disease to the horse (a relatively frequent case and is subject to epidemiological surveillance; as noted above, 2 horses have recently developed the disease in Upper Corsica) or, more rarely, to humans.

But since this summer [2018], the Mediterranean region has been hit by increased numbers of human cases. In addition to the 22 confirmed cases in Paca, 1300 infected persons were recently reported in Europe. A total of 3 persons died this summer in the Ferrara region of Italy from West Nile fever. "This year, we are actually seeing a much earlier and more severe circulation of the virus throughout the Mediterranean," says Dr. McKenzie.

But the good news is that unlike other arboviroses, such as chikungunya, dengue or Zika, humans and horses are "accidental hosts." "The latter are epidemiological dead ends," says the doctor of the ARS, "that is to say that they cannot transmit the virus. A mosquito that would bite an infected person cannot carry the virus and infect another person, which significantly reduces the chain of contamination."

To limit the risk of an epidemic, the ARS renews its message of prevention: "The only thing to do is to protect oneself from mosquitoes. We must be vigilant, prevent [the mosquitoes] from proliferating by fighting against their roosting and using repellents."

[Byline: C. Marcelin]

